The paper discusses a Bayesian framework for density estimation using Dirichlet process mixture models. The focus is on finding a maximum a posteriori assignment of data points to clusters, which suggests a machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG, cs.AI) focus. The paper also discusses the computational expense of inference in DP mixture models, which suggests a focus on algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The experimental results involve applying DP mixture models to large data sets, which suggests a focus on statistics (cs.ST) and computer vision (cs.CV).
